articles.description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has stated that a ceasefire in the conflict with Hamas will not happen, as the UN warns that there is not enough aid coming in to meet the "unprecedented humanitarian needs" in Gaza. The Israeli ground forces have been fighting inside the Gaza Strip and carrying out air strikes on the Hamas-controlled territory. The intensifying military operations have increased concerns for the 2.4 million inhabitants of Gaza, where over 8,300 people have been killed.
articles.title: Israel PM rejects Gaza ceasefire as 'surrender to Hamas'

articles.description: Israeli troops and tanks have advanced further into Gaza, with airstrikes hitting closer to hospitals where Palestinians have sought shelter. Video footage shows an Israeli tank blocking the main highway and opening fire on a car, killing three people. Israel has been vague about its operations in Gaza but recent movements suggest a focus on the main city. The death toll among Palestinians has passed 8,300, with over 1.4 million people in Gaza fleeing their homes. Hospitals in northern Gaza are under threat, with strikes hitting near several medical facilities.
articles.title: Israel Troops Advance On Gaza City

China claims almost the entire South China Sea, which has fueled maritime tensions and territorial disputes in the region.

Cornell Hillel condemned the threats, and the New York governor increased security on campuses. Prosecution of those responsible is emphasized.

articles.description: Ray Holmberg, a retired Republican state senator from North Dakota, has been indicted on charges of traveling to Europe with the intent of engaging in sexual activity with a minor and receiving images depicting child sexual abuse. Holmberg, who served for over 45 years in the North Dakota Senate, has pleaded not guilty and is scheduled for trial in December. The indictment alleges that he made multiple trips to Prague between 2011 and 2016 and used aliases during these activities.
articles.title: Ex-North Dakota lawmaker charged with travelling to Prague for sex with minor

articles.description: Over 100 professors at Columbia University have signed a letter in support of students who expressed their views on the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. The professors called for protection of the students from potential negative consequences and for the university to halt its educational initiatives in Israel. They also requested that the administration refrain from favoring one side in the conflict. The professors argue that expressing empathy for Palestinians and calling for an end to the illegal occupation of Palestinian territory is not a radical or controversial opinion.
articles.title: Over 100 Columbia University professors sign letter backing students who supported Hamas’ Oct 7 attack

articles.description: A frigid blast of air is sweeping across the United States, with nearly 250 million Americans experiencing unusually cold weather. Temperature records are at risk of being broken in several states, except for Florida. The cold front will reach its peak later this week, with temperatures dropping to single digits in the northern Plains and teens in the central and southern Plains. Morning lows in the southern Plains will dip into the 20s and 30s.
articles.title: US temperature plummets as artic blast threatens record-low chill

articles.description: Multiple shootings occurred across the United States over the weekend before Halloween, resulting in at least 11 deaths and over 70 injuries. The incidents, which took place in various states including Florida, Texas, Kansas, and Ohio, were often related to altercations arising from Halloween celebrations. The shootings have reignited concerns about gun violence in America, with advocates calling for stricter gun control measures. Several suspects have been arrested in connection with the shootings.
articles.title: Halloween weekend shootings across US leave at least 11 dead, scores injured

articles.description: Indian American former South Carolina Governor Nikki Haley has tied with Florida Governor Ron DeSantis for second position in the race for the next US President, according to a new poll. Both candidates have 16% support, with Haley experiencing a 10% increase while DeSantis saw a 3% drop. The former President Donald Trump remains the frontrunner with 43% support. Other candidates have not reached double digits in terms of support percentage. The poll also revealed that 54% of likely GOP caucus-goers are open to being persuaded to support someone other than their first choice.
articles.title: Haley ties for second with DeSantis while Trump leads in Iowa poll

articles.description: Lebanon's caretaker prime minister, Najib Mikati, is working to prevent his country from being dragged into the Hamas-Israel war. He expressed concerns about an escalation and the possibility of Hezbollah, an ally of Hamas, opening a new front with Israel. Mikati, who is on good terms with Hezbollah, stated that he cannot reassure the Lebanese people as the situation is still developing. He also warned of the potential for chaos engulfing the entire Middle East.
articles.title: Lebanon PM says working to avoid 'war' with Israel

articles.description: With a significant number of Canadian mortgages set to renew in the next three years, homeowners may face a substantial increase in monthly payments unless interest rates decline. RBC Capital Markets analyst Darko Mihelic predicts payment shocks of up to 48% in 2026, particularly for those with negatively amortizing loans. The report suggests that the Bank of Canada's overnight rate would need to decline significantly to mitigate the payment shock for borrowers.
articles.title: Payment shock coming for most Canadians with mortgages, RBC says

articles.description: President Joe Biden is set to sign an executive order on Monday to guide the development of artificial intelligence (AI). The order will require industry to develop safety and security standards, introduce new consumer protections, and give federal agencies oversight of the technology. It reflects the government's effort to shape the evolution of AI in a way that maximizes its potential while mitigating its risks. The order will also require leading AI developers to share safety test results with the government and establish standards to ensure AI tools are safe and secure before public release.
articles.title: Biden wants to move fast on AI safeguards and will sign an executive order to address his concerns

articles.description: Rest of World News: OTTAWA: Canada on Monday banned Chinese messaging application WeChat and Russian antivirus program Kaspersky on government-issued mobile devices due t.
articles.title: Canada bans WeChat, Kaspersky applications on government devices

articles.description: The European Union plans to invest 6 billion euros in the countries of the Western Balkans to support their integration with the EU. The EU's president, Ursula von der Leyen, emphasized the need for these countries to align their standards with those of the EU and seize the opportunity for enlargement. The EU's growth plan for the region includes opening its common market to the Western Balkan countries and calls for necessary reforms. The EU aims to double the economies of these countries.
articles.title: EU to help Western Balkans reforms with 6 billion euro package: Von der Leyen

articles.description: Chinese President Xi Jinping has emphasized the importance of women in addressing the country's ageing population and declining birth rate. In a meeting with the All China Women's Federation, Xi stated that women's role is not only crucial for their own development but also for family harmony, social harmony, and national progress. He called for the cultivation of a new culture of marriage and childbearing, as factors such as high childcare costs and gender discrimination have deterred young Chinese women from having children.
articles.title: Xi says China's women must start 'new trend of family'

articles.description: An analyst suggests that the recent riot at Makhachkala Uytash Airport, in which Muslims attempted to attack Jews, was likely fueled by Iran and other extreme Islamic groups. The Russian authorities were not supporting the event. The attack occurred after a Hamas delegation visited Moscow. The rioters overran the airport, searching for Israeli passengers, and made threats against Jews. The incident is expected to strain diplomatic relations between Russia and Israel. The airport will remain closed until November 6.
articles.title: Dagestan airport riot 'probably fueled by Iran,' says expert

articles.description: A survey by the Lowy Institute's Pacific Aid Map found that the Pacific Islands is the most aid-reliant region in the world. Between 2008 and 2021, the region received over $40 billion in development assistance, with direct budget support to Pacific Island governments increasing to 40% in 2021. Climate-related aid accounted for 39% of all aid pledged to the region in 2021, but the Lowy report noted that climate financing remains insufficient. Australia is the largest donor to the Pacific Islands, followed by China.
articles.title: Pacific Islands is world's most aid-reliant region: report

articles.description: The Russian authorities have blamed "external interference" for the recent anti-Israel protests in the country. Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov stated that the events were largely the result of external interference and that President Vladimir Putin would discuss the situation with his advisers. The riots occurred in Russia's predominantly Muslim republic, with reports of protesters storming the main airport in the capital. Around 20 people were injured, 60 were arrested, and over 150 participants were identified.
articles.title: Russia blames 'outside influence' for airport mob

articles.description: A former British intelligence worker, Joshua Bowles, has been sentenced to 13 years in jail for attempting to murder a US National Security Agency (NSA) employee. Bowles, who had previously worked at the British intelligence agency GCHQ, stabbed the woman outside a leisure centre in Cheltenham in March. He stated that he targeted her due to her employment at the NSA, believing that American intelligence was the largest contributor in the intelligence community.
articles.title: Ex-British intelligence worker jailed for attempted murder of US NSA employee

articles.description: The month-long Vatican meeting on the future of the Roman Catholic Church ended without clear positions on issues such as women deacons and LGBT inclusion. The meeting, called a Synod of Bishops, allowed women and lay people to vote on Church affairs for the first time. However, the final report did not take a stand on LGBT issues despite discussions beforehand. The report mentioned the need to hear and accompany marginalized individuals but did not call for greater inclusion. LGBT advocates expressed disappointment with the report. The pope will close the gathering with a Mass on Sunday.
articles.title: Vatican synod ends without clear stances on women, LGBT community

articles.description: The extensive tunnel network built by the Hamas militant group in the Gaza Strip poses a significant threat to Israeli troops and the Palestinian population. Clearing and collapsing these tunnels is crucial for dismantling Hamas, but it is a challenging task that strips the Israeli military of its technological advantages. The tunnels provide Hamas with hiding places and the ability to choose the time and location of engagement. Israeli airstrikes have targeted these tunnels, but combating underground warfare is difficult due to the abundance of ambush opportunities.
articles.title: Hamas militants holed up in 'Metro' web of tunnels pose challenge

articles.description: The ongoing conflict in Gaza has not only resulted in the loss of lives but has also disrupted the funeral rites of Palestinians, depriving them of dignity and closure. The high number of casualties has overwhelmed hospitals and morgues, making it difficult to perform traditional funeral rituals. Many bodies are unrecognizable due to decomposition or the absence of surviving family members. In an attempt to increase the chances of identification, families are resorting to wearing identification bracelets and writing names on their children's bodies.
articles.title: Mass graves & a city robbed of funeral rites

articles.description: On Saturday, the European Union and Japan reached an agreement to promote cross-border data flows, aimed at enhancing online trade between businesses and combating digital protectionism, as reported by the European Union. This pact was signed during the G7 trade ministers' meeting in Osaka and is designed to streamline online business operations, making them more convenient, cost-effective, and efficient, according to a statement from the European Commission.
articles.title: European Union, Japan strike data flows deal

articles.description: US Republican presidential candidates expressed their unwavering support for Israel and vowed to wipe out Palestinian Hamas militants during a gathering of major Jewish donors in Las Vegas. The event, organized by the Republican Jewish Coalition, comes at a time when Israel is preparing for a ground invasion of Gaza following an attack by Hamas. The candidates, including frontrunner Donald Trump, emphasized their commitment to Israel and criticized any isolationist tendencies within the Republican Party.
articles.title: US Republican presidential candidates tout Israel support in speeches to Jewish donors

articles.description: US and Chinese officials have reached an agreement in principle for a meeting between Presidents Joe Biden and Xi Jinping next month. The details and arrangements for the meeting are still being worked out, but it is likely to take place during the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit in San Francisco. The breakthrough follows Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi's visit to Washington, where he met with Secretary of State Antony Blinken and National Security Advisor Jake Sullivan.
articles.title: US, China agree in principle on Biden-Xi meeting in Nov

articles.description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has announced that the military has entered a "second stage" in the war against Hamas by sending ground forces into Gaza. He stated that attacks will increase ahead of a broader ground invasion and that the mission is to destroy Hamas' military and governmental capabilities and bring back the hostages. The bombardment has severely disrupted communications and paralyzed the health network in Gaza. Hamas has expressed readiness for an immediate prisoner swap with Israel.
articles.title: Israel expands ground operations; Gaza war enters 'second stage'

articles.description: A mariner who went missing off the Washington coast has been found alive in a life raft, but his companion is still missing. The two mariners set off on October 12 from Westport, Washington, but failed to return as scheduled. The Coast Guard conducted a search operation but suspended it due to a lack of leads. A Good Samaritan vessel discovered the life raft with one of the mariners inside, who managed to survive by catching and consuming a salmon.
articles.title: Fisherman missing for two weeks found alive off Washington coast

articles.description: The death toll from Hurricane Otis in Mexico has been raised to 39, with the cause of death being suffocation by submersion. The number of missing has also increased to 10. The recovery effort has been slow, with aid taking several days to arrive. Gasoline and food shortages are also being reported, with some people resorting to looting to obtain supplies. The destruction caused by the Category 5 storm has left many areas without electricity and access to basic necessities like water.
articles.title: Mexico security authorities raise Hurricane Otis death toll to 39

articles.description: Middle East News: CAIRO: Egypt's military spokesman on Sunday said an unspecified number of border guards sustained "minor injuries" from "fragments of a shell accident.
articles.title: Egypt army reports 'minor injuries' in accidental Israeli shelling

articles.description: An Army reservist who killed 18 people at a Maine bowling alley and bar purchased his weapons legally, according to authorities. The shooter, identified as Robert Card, died of an apparent self-inflicted gunshot wound. He had a history of mental illness, including hearing voices and expressing a desire to harm others. Card had not been involuntarily committed to a mental health facility, and a simple evaluation or voluntary commitment would not have prohibited him from owning a gun.
articles.title: Maine mass killing suspect had mental health issues, purchased guns legally, authorities say

articles.description: Prime Minister Narendra Modi and Egyptian President Abdel Fattah El-Sisi had a phone call to discuss the ongoing Israeli military operations in the Gaza Strip. They expressed concern about the impact on civilians and the region's security. El-Sisi confirmed Egypt's efforts to coordinate international actions towards a ceasefire and warned against a ground offensive. Both leaders emphasized their commitment to strengthening bilateral relations and cooperation between Egypt and India.
articles.title: PM Modi, Egyptian President discuss Israel-Hamas conflict

articles.description: A 75-year-old mother in Italy has taken legal action against her two sons in their 40s who refused to leave the family home. The sons, despite having jobs, had been living with their mother for an extended period and not contributing to the household. The mother sought help from the judicial system and a judge issued an eviction order against the sons. This case highlights the societal issue in Italy of adults, particularly those aged 18 to 34, continuing to live with their parents.
articles.title: Italian mother takes her two sons in their 40s to court, gets them evicted

articles.description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu announced that Israeli forces have entered the second phase of the war in Gaza, as they continue their ground operations against Hamas militants. The Gaza Strip is currently facing a humanitarian crisis, with limited communication with the outside world and a shortage of basic necessities. Netanyahu stated that the goal of the war is to destroy Hamas' capabilities and bring home the hostages held by the group.
articles.title: Israel launches Gaza war's second phase with ground operation, Netanyahu says

articles.description: Prince Harry and Meghan Markle's differing views on wealth are reportedly causing tension in their relationship. While Harry prioritizes charity work and family life, Meghan is focused on developing her personal brand for financial gains, potentially through sponsored posts on social media. Speculations about their financial priorities come amid reports of strain in their relationship, with experts advising them to remain a united front for the sake of their joint professional and financial endeavors.
articles.title: Money matters creating wedge between Harry, Meghan

articles.description: Israel's Foreign Minister, Eli Cohen, has ordered the return of diplomatic representatives from Turkey to reassess the country's relations with Turkey. This decision comes after Turkish leaders condemned Israel's military campaign against Hamas. Israeli ambassadors stationed in Turkey have been instructed to return to Israel. Turkey's President, Recep Tayyip Erdogan, referred to Hamas as 'mujahideen' defending their lands and cancelled his visit to Israel. Turkey's Foreign Minister, Hakan Fidan, accused Israel of committing "a crime against humanity" in its war in Gaza.
articles.title: Israel to reassess diplomatic relations with Turkey, says Foreign Minister Cohen

articles.description: Over 20,000 people marched through Johannesburg in support of LGBTQ+ communities in Africa who face criminalization and cannot openly express their identities. The parade was led by a Ugandan man who had fled his country after being arrested for being gay. The march aimed to raise awareness for LGBT rights in Africa, particularly in Uganda, where the death penalty for homosexuality was introduced in May. South Africa, in contrast, legalized same-sex marriage in 2006 and is the only African country to have done so.
articles.title: Johannesburg Pride marches for LGBTQ+ Ugandans after anti-gay law passed

articles.description: College campuses in the United States are experiencing a surge in activism surrounding the Israel-Palestine conflict. This activism is characterized by dueling protests and debates, with both pro-Palestinian and Jewish students facing harassment and online attacks. The divisive nature of the conflict, combined with the influence of social media, has led to a lack of consensus among students. This activism has also had broader implications, with some colleges facing accusations of antisemitism and losing donor support.
articles.title: Tension rise in US universities amid Israel-Hamas war

articles.description: Serbian police have dispatched hundreds of officers to a border area with Hungary after a shooting between migrants resulted in three deaths and one injury. The incident occurred near the Serbia-Hungary border, where reports of violence and gun battles have become common. Thousands of migrants have been camping in the area, attempting to cross into EU member nation Hungary with the help of people smugglers. Police actions are aimed at curbing irregular migration and increasing security in the region. Several have been detained, including individuals suspected of smuggling migrants.
articles.title: Hundreds of Serbian police deploy in border zone with Hungary after deadly shooting among migrants

articles.description: UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres expressed surprise at Israel's escalation of bombardments in Gaza and called for an immediate humanitarian ceasefire. Guterres stated that instead of a pause, there has been an unprecedented escalation that undermines humanitarian objectives. The escalation follows Israel's reprisal for an attack by Hamas, resulting in a humanitarian catastrophe for Gaza's 2.3 million people. The communication blackout in Gaza is impeding aid efforts, including ambulances and evacuations.
articles.title: UN chief surprised by escalation of Israel's bombardment, calls for humanitarian ceasefire

Buildings destroyed after the earthquake on February 13, 2023, in Hatay, Turkey. | Murat Saka/dia images via Getty Images
    

  
Turkey is investigating and has arrested some contractors, but the entire political and economic system is implicated.
 Turkey is still in the middle of an emergency, reeling from the earthquake that killed at least 35,000 people last week. But the finger-pointing has already begun. 
The rush to punishment comes amid the grief, but also the mounting fury and frustration over the Turkish government’s earthquake response. Much of that is focused on the emergency response — waiting for aid and rescue teams — but it is also extending to anger about policies before the earthquake, about how shoddy building construction may have exacerbated the devastation of the dis…
articles.title: Who is responsible for Turkey’s bad buildings?

articles.description:
Getty Images
    

  
How we turned 20,000 Soviet nukes into zero-carbon energy — and how we can do the same with some of our own.
 Just a decade ago, one in 10 American lightbulbs was powered by dismantled Russian nuclear weapons.
That was made possible by the Megatons to Megawatts program, an agreement negotiated after the collapse of the Soviet Union to convert uranium from Russia’s nuclear weapons stockpile into fuel for US nuclear power plants. The unconventional policy was first proposed by MIT physicist Thomas Neff in a 1991 New York Times op-ed. By the time Megatons to Megawatts ran its full course from 1993 to 2013, it had eliminated about 20,000 nuclear warheads and stood out as a point of shared pride in the often jaded arms control and disarmament field. “Nearly every commercia…
articles.title: 10 years ago, we were turning nuclear bombs into nuclear energy. We can do it again.

articles.description:
Volunteers stand on rubble of a destroyed building in Kahramanmaras, Turkey, on February 7, 2023. | Adem Altan/AFP via Getty Images
    

  
What Turkey and Syria’s deadly earthquakes reveal about wealth.
 In the early hours of Monday, February 6, residents living in southern Turkey and northern Syria were woken by violent shaking, collapsing buildings, and sweeping blackouts. The earthquake buried residents in rubble and was followed by powerful aftershocks. By the following Monday, the death toll had passed 36,000 people. “It was like the apocalypse,” Abdul Salam al-Mahmoud, a resident of Atareb, Syria, told Reuters.  
The country is no stranger to quakes, having lost 17,000 people to a 7.4-magnitude tremor in 1999. But while last week’s earthquake was a 7.8-magnitude quake, and had an u…
articles.title: Why earthquakes are deadlier depending on where you live

articles.description:
A suspected Chinese spy balloon flies above Charlotte, North Carolina, on February 4, 2023.  | Peter Zay/Anadolu Agency via Getty Images
    

  
As all these objects fall, a new space race is rising.
 Now that the US military has shot down a suspected spy balloon from China and three other unidentified flying objects, there will be debates about the UFOs’ meaning, their capabilities, and why they were all up there in the first place. 
Though former CIA Director Michael Hayden said the initial balloon’s threat to the welfare of Americans was vastly inflated, others described the incident as a wake-up call. Former Trump national security adviser H.R. McMaster hopes it will lead to a “Sputnik moment,” harkening back to the US space race with the Soviet Union. The Wall Street Journal even war…
articles.title: Why the balloon and UFO affairs are a Sputnik moment

CBS host Margaret Brennan grilled Sen. J.D. Vance (R-OH) on Sunday after he said he opposed aid to children in Gaza because he insisted it would go to the terror group Hamas. 
While Vance agreed that there are "a lot of innocent people in Gaza," he insisted that terrorists would intercept the aid packages.
"So if you deliver a large amount of humanitarian assistance, who's it going to go to?" he asked. "The children in Gaza or to the Hamas fighters on the front line? I fear it's going to go to Hamas."
POLL: Should Trump be allowed to run for office?

Brennan pointed out that international organizations like the Red Cross were distributing the aid.
"But I think there's still a lot of evidence with a lot of these international organizations that when we send aid into Gaza, a lot of it goes into the wrong hands," Vance said. "We don't want to basically fund two sides of the exact same conflict. Fund Hamas, fund Israel."
ALSO READ: Sen. J.D. Vance finally dumps stock in 'slave labor' company
"Well, it's not aid to Hamas," Brennan observed. "It's aid to the Palestinian people."
"And if I could wave a magic wand and give aid to the Palestinian children, I will," Vance quipped.
Watch the video below from CBS or at the link.
articles.title: 'It's not aid to Hamas': CBS host grills J.D. Vance for opposing funds for Gaza kids

articles.description:
Prime Minister Anthony Albanese says US President Joe Biden welcomed the fact that he is going to meet China’s leader, Xi Jinping. 

Mr Albanese’s remarks come after the Prime Minister wrapped up a state visit to the United States, strengthening ties and pushing for key AUKUS legislation to be passed this year. 

A major theme of the visit was policy in the Indo-Pacific, particularly towards China, and US President Joe Biden had some pointed criticism for the People’s Republic ahead of the Prime Minister’s visit to China in November.  

“Australia and China have different political systems, of course, and different values,” Mr Albanese told Sky News Political Editor Andrew Clennell. 

“One of the reasons why the relationship with the United States is so close is because we do have that common commitment to human rights, to democracy, and to our values. 

“It’s important that Australia stabilise the relationship – that’s something that the US is seeking as well.”
articles.title: Joe Biden welcomed Anthony Albanese’s expected visit to China to meet Xi Jinping

articles.description:
Hamas leader Ismail Haniyeh and other Hamas leaders leading a prayer before hosting an Iftar Ramadan fast-breaking dinner in Qatar with Qatari officials and international diplomats April 13, 2023. (Hamas.ps)

 

Times of Israel: Far from Gaza hardships, Hamas chief and family enjoy easy life in Qatar

 
Thanks to Doha’s sponsorship and the wealth he accumulated as Hamas leader, Ismail Haniyeh and his children today live a life of wealth and privileges denied to other Gazans 
Shortly after the start of Hamas’s brutal attack against Israel on October 7, a video began circulating of the terror group’s leader Ismail Haniyeh in his elegant office in the Qatari capital Doha, watching the bloody onslaught unfold on Al Jazeera and “prostrating in gratitude” with a group of other Hamas officials for the killing of over 1,300 Israelis, among them at least 1,000 civilians.
For years, Haniyeh has been rebuked by many Palestinians for leading a comfortable life away from the hardships of Gaza in the oil-rich Gulf monarchy, which offers shelter to the terror group’s leaders and an internationally recognized platform to spread its propaganda through Al Jazeera.

 
Read more .... 
 WNU Editor: Hamas leader Ismail Haniyeh is not the only leader leader who is protected and far away from the war that he has helped to ignite. Almost all of the world's leaders are protected and immune from the policies and strategies that they implement.
articles.title: Hamas Leader And Family Enjoy An Easy Life In Qatar

.@LeaderMcConnell says "a significant portion" of Ukraine aid from Congress is being spent in states to make weapons.
"We're rebuilding our industrial base. The Ukrainians are destroying the army of one of our biggest rivals. I have a hard time finding anything wrong with that." pic.twitter.com/24janX3kbr
— Face The Nation (@FaceTheNation) October 22, 2023
  
The Federalist: No Mitch McConnell, Ukraine Aid Is Not ‘Rebuilding Our Industrial Base’ 
Senate Republican Minority Leader Mitch McConnell wants to reassure Ukrainian aid skeptics that billions in foreign assistance is being spent on American manufacturers to build weapons at home. 
“If you look at the Ukraine assistance,” McConnell said on CBS, “a significant portion of what’s being spent in the United States and 38 different states, replacing the weapons that we send to Ukraine with more modern weapons, so we’re rebuilding our industrial base.” 
But a closer examination of the aid for Ukraine reveals an overwhelming majority of taxpayer dollars are going overseas. Just a fraction of the $113 billion spent has gone to “rebuilding our industrial base.”

 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: Defense spending always boosts the economy, but after the stimulus it is always followed by inflation and economic contraction. And as for rebuilding America's industrial base. I doubt it.
articles.title: Is U.S. Aid To Ukraine Rebuilding America's Industrial Base?

Responsible Statecraft:  Tracking the US military build-up today in the Middle East 
An up-to-date accounting of the Pentagon’s response to the Israel-Gaza conflict so far. 
The U.S. has significantly increased its military presence in the Middle East in the nearly three weeks after Hamas launched attacks against Israel and took hundreds of hostages on Oct. 7. Among other things, the Pentagon has deployed two aircraft carrier strike groups as well as a range of fighter aircraft to the region. 
The official reason for the new deployments is to deter Hamas’s allies, including Iran and Hezbollah, from launching attacks against Israel and sparking a wider regional war. That logic will be put to the test in the coming days if Israel follows through on its planned ground invasion of Gaza, which is sure to face sharp condemnation from throughout the Middle East.

 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: 50+ warships and submarines and counting. This is a massive deployment that is far more than what is needed as a deterrent.
articles.title: Massive U.S. And NATO Naval Buildup In The Eastern Mediterranean Continues

The European Union has delivered only a third of the one million artillery shells it had promised to Ukraine, as the bloc’s plan to ramp up munition production falls behind schedule.

CNN: Tuberville says he will keep blocking military promotions despite Israel’s war  
Republican Sen. Tommy Tuberville, who has held up military promotions for nine months, slammed a proposal being floated to change the chamber’s rules to allow a vote on many of the nominations en masse and attacked the White House and Senate Democrats for not negotiating with him. 
“It’s typical of this place. This administration would rather burn the Senate down and that’s what would happen. … If you change the rules of the Senate then it lasts forever,” Tuberville told CNN’s Manu Raju. “So they would rather burn down the Senate than negotiate.”

The F-15EX, designated EX3, is expected to be delivered soon, ahead of the decision for the full rate production. 
After more than two years after the type’s first flight, Boeing flew for the first time the third F-15EX Eagle II, which is also the first to be built in the final operational configuration. 
The aircraft flew only with its primer paint and a small serial number (20-0003) on its twin tails, and will receive its final colors and insignias before the delivery to the U.S. Air Force.

President Joe Biden walks along a stretch of the U.S.-Mexico border in El Paso Texas, Jan. 8, 2023. Andrew Harnik,AP 

 The Center Square:  Illegal border crossers total over 10 million since Biden inauguration

 
Total is greater than the individual populations of 41 states  
More than 10 million people have been reported illegally entering the United States since President Joe Biden took office in January 2021, the greatest number in history and of any administration. 
They total more than the individual populations of 41 states. 
The number of people illegally entering the country surged after Biden and Department of Homeland Security Secretary Alejandro Mayorkas halted many preexisting border security policies, advanced sweeping parole and other policies to release the greatest number of illegal foreign nationals into the country, encouraged people from all over the world to use a phone app to enter the U.S., and facilitated U.S. entry application processes in foreign countries, among others.

 
Read more ....

Al Jazeera: Palestinians break into Gaza UN aid warehouses as toll tops 8,000 
Thousands of people storm food warehouses in Gaza to take flour and basic needs in a mark of growing desperation. 
The United Nations relief agency says thousands of Palestinians, desperate due to three weeks of total siege and bombing, broke into several of its warehouses in the Gaza Strip, taking wheat, flour and other basic goods. 
“This is a worrying sign that civil order is starting to break down after three weeks of war and a tight siege,” said Thomas White, director of the UN Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees (UNRWA) in Gaza.

 
Read more ....

This startling declaration came amid the escalating conflict in Gaza, as the death toll of Palestinian citizens continues to rise.

The Turkish president called for a just peace and accused Israel and its allies of fostering a crusade-like atmosphere, further escalating tensions in the region.

Hamas Handout/Handout via REUTERS © Thomson Reuters

 

Moscow Times/AFP: Hamas Working to Free 8 Russian-Israeli Hostages – Reports 
Hamas is trying to locate eight Russian-Israeli dual citizens among nearly 230 taken hostage during its attack on Israel after Moscow's request to free them, Russian news agencies reported Saturday. 
Russia has good relations with the Palestinian militant group, which it does not consider a terror group, and has launched a diplomatic effort to try to free hostages held in Gaza.

Israel has said it believes 229 people were taken hostage by Hamas during its massive attack on Israel on Oct. 7. 
"From the Russian side, via the Foreign Ministry, we received a list of citizens that have dual citizenship," senior Hamas representative Moussa Abu Marzook said, the RIA Novosti news agency reported.

"We are looking for those people... It is hard but we are looking. And when we find them, we will let them go."

 
Read more ....

France 24: Kosovo, Serbia leaders break off talks despite EU pressure for breakthrough

 
EU leaders on Thursday failed to convince Kosovo and Serbia to make a breakthrough in the protracted push to normalise ties between the two Balkan neighbours. 
Kosovan Prime Minister Albin Kurti and Serbian President Aleksandar Vucic held separate talks with top EU officials and the leaders of France, Germany and Italy in Brussels.

EU foreign policy chief Josep Borrell said a proposal was put on the table to overcome a key stumbling block on establishing an association of municipalities of Serbian majority in the north of Kosovo. 
"Unhappily, the parties were not ready to agree on that, without preconditions that were unacceptable to the other party," Borrell said. "We will continue insisting and working in order to get an agreement," he added. 
The two Balkan leaders blamed each other for the failure of the talks.

 
Read more ....

 
Update: Serbia and Kosovo leaders break off talks without result despite EU pressure (AP)

 
WNU Editor: This is not going to happen .... European leaders urge Serbia to 'de facto' recognise Kosovo (Reuters).
articles.title: Serbia - Kosovo Talks Break Down

Russian planes reportedly have mined the maritime corridor that Ukraine established in the western Black Sea in order to safeguard the export of grain to Europe and Africa. 
It seems to be the first time in Russia’s 21-month wider war that the Russian Black Sea Fleet’s aircraft have deployed sea mines.

Ukraine’s southern command reported the ominous development on Wednesday. 
“The enemy ... dropped four unidentified means of impact, probably bottom mines, in the Black Sea ... in the direction of navigation corridors of civil shipping,” the command stated.

Military Times/AP: No, the US military isn’t ‘laying the groundwork’ for a draft

 
Claim: The U.S. military is planning to reinstitute the draft.

 
AP’s Assessment: False. Defense officials confirm the armed forces have made no such recommendation to Congress or the president, which are the entities empowered to authorize a draft.

 
The Facts: With America’s allies in Europe and the Middle East embroiled in conflicts with no end in sight, social media posts are claiming the U.S. military is considering mandating regular citizens to enlist in the armed forces. 
A number of those are sharing a headline from a Sept. 25 article from the Mises Institute, a libertarian group in Alabama that reads: “The US Military Is Laying the Groundwork to Reinstitute the Draft.”

 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: "U.S. military draft"  has been trending on search engines for the past few weeks. Videos like the one above and rumors on social media are probably fueling it .... Video of Biden calling for a military draft is AI-generated, not real | Fact check (USA Today). More here .... Fighting 'Joe Biden's wars': False rumor of 'draft' spreads across social media as 'medicated' Gen Z slammed for not signing up (Meaww), and here .... Fact Check: Video of Joe Biden calling for a military draft was created with AI (Reuters).
Just one more note. 
On the eve of Russia's invasion of Ukraine the Kyiv government was telling everyone to not worry, and to stay home. Within 24 hours of Russia's invasion, the Ukraine government immediately closed its border to men of military age who can be drafted. The U.S. government will do the same. Telling everyone that everything is fine, until the very moment that the "shit hits the fan".
articles.title: Is The US Military ‘Laying The Groundwork’ To Reinstitute the Draft? The Pentagon Says No

Warzone: B-21 Raider Has Begun Taxi Tests 
The Air Force is hopeful that the B-21 Raider stealth bomber will take to the skies for the first time before the end of the year. 
The U.S. Air Force's first pre-production B-21 Raider stealth bomber is now undergoing taxi testing, moving around the sprawling Plant 42 in Palmdale under its own power. This is the latest developmental milestone for the aircraft as it continues to move closer to its first flight, which could come before the end of the year. 
"I can confirm the B-21 is conducting ground taxi activities. Rigorous testing is a critical step in the B-21 flight test program," an Air Force spokesperson confirmed to The War Zone today. "Extensive testing evaluates systems, components, and functionalities. This testing allows us to mitigate risks, optimize design, and enhance operational effectiveness." 
Read more .... 
 
WNU Editor: The first contracts for production of the B-21 are being drawn up .... Northrop expects B-21 low-rate production contract by year-end (Flight Global).

Wikipedia 

Reuters: US halts exports of most civilian firearms for 90 days 
WASHINGTON (Reuters) -The U.S. has stopped issuing export licenses for most civilian firearms and ammunition for 90 days for all non-governmental users, the Commerce Department said on Friday, citing national security and foreign policy interests. 
The Commerce Department did not provide further details for the pause, which also includes shotguns and optical sights, but said an urgent review will assess the "risk of firearms being diverted to entities or activities that promote regional instability, violate human rights, or fuel criminal activities."

 
Read more ....

 
WNU editor: This is unprecedented. The only exceptions to this export ban are Israel and Ukraine. 
So why the ban and this hoarding of weapons and ammo? 
My gut tells me that with US military stockpiles now at an all time low and supply chain disruptions are  growing. In this environment the US has made the decision that with international relations deteriorating and threats of a major war growing everyday, the US needs to replenish some of their stockpiles ASAP.
articles.title: US Halts Most Civilian Firearm And Ammunition Exports For 90 Days
